go:term.go:name: biological_process
go:term.go:definition: Any process specifically pertinent to the functioning of integrated living units: cells, tissues, organs, and organisms. A process is a collection of molecular events with a defined beginning and end.
go:term.go:comment: Note that, in addition to forming the root of the biological process ontology, this term is recommended for use for the annotation of gene products whose biological process is unknown. Note that when this term is used for annotation, it indicates that no information was available about the biological process of the gene product annotated as of the date the annotation was made; the evidence code ND, no data, is used to indicate this.

go:term.go:name: molecular_function
go:term.go:definition: Elemental activities, such as catalysis or binding, describing the actions of a gene product at the molecular level. A given gene product may exhibit one or more molecular functions.
go:term.go:comment: Note that, in addition to forming the root of the molecular function ontology, this term is recommended for use for the annotation of gene products whose molecular function is unknown. Note that when this term is used for annotation, it indicates that no information was available about the molecular function of the gene product annotated as of the date the annotation was made; the evidence code ND, no data, is used to indicate this.

go:term.go:name: cellular_component
go:term.go:definition: The part of a cell or its extracellular environment in which a gene product is located. A gene product may be located in one or more parts of a cell and its location may be as specific as a particular macromolecular complex, that is, a stable, persistent association of macromolecules that function together.
go:term.go:comment: Note that, in addition to forming the root of the cellular component ontology, this term is recommended for use for the annotation of gene products whose cellular component is unknown. Note that when this term is used for annotation, it indicates that no information was available about the cellular component of the gene product annotated as of the date the annotation was made; the evidence code ND, no data, is used to indicate this.

go:term.go:name: obsolete molecular function
go:term.go:definition: OBSOLETE. These are terms that have been removed from the active function ontology.
go:term.go:comment: This term was made obsolete because it is unnecessary in the OBO flat file format.

go:term.go:name: obsolete cellular component
go:term.go:definition: OBSOLETE. These are terms that have been removed from the active component ontology.
go:term.go:comment: This term was made obsolete because it is unnecessary in the OBO flat file format.

go:term.go:name: obsolete biological process
go:term.go:definition: OBSOLETE. These are terms that have been removed from the active process ontology.
go:term.go:comment: This term was made obsolete because it is unnecessary in the OBO flat file format.

go:term.go:name: death
go:term.go:definition: A permanent cessation of all vital functions: the end of life; can be applied to a whole organism or to a part of an organism.
go:term.go:comment: See also the biological process term 'apoptosis ; GO:0006915'.

go:term.go:name: cellular process
go:term.go:definition: Any process that is carried out at the cellular level, but not necessarily restricted to a single cell. For example, cell communication occurs among more than one cell, but occurs at the cellular level.

go:term.go:name: cell death
go:term.go:definition: A biological process that results in permanent cessation of all vital functions of a cell.

go:term.go:name: cytolysis
go:term.go:definition: The rupture of cell membranes and the loss of cytoplasm.

go:term.go:name: autolysis
go:term.go:definition: The spontaneous death by lysis of bacteria in response to environmental conditions.

go:term.go:name: negative regulation of cytolysis
go:term.go:definition: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of cytolysis.

go:term.go:name: regulation of cytolysis
go:term.go:definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the rupture of cell membranes and the loss of cytoplasm.

go:term.go:name: regulation of cell death
go:term.go:definition: Any process that modulates the rate or frequency of cell death. Cell death is the specific activation or halting of processes within a cell so that its vital functions markedly cease, rather than simply deteriorating gradually over time, which culminates in cell death.

go:term.go:name: regulation of biological process
go:term.go:definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of a biological process. Biological processes are regulated by many means; examples include the control of gene expression, protein modification or interaction with a protein or substrate molecule.
